@chrisjcook I think I was mainly trying to give my perspective. I agree with all you wrote. But then I ask myself: now what?

What I wonder comes down to "change what exists" vs. "build better from the ground up". Changing what exists seems to be a (very) slow process. I'm involved in building the new and although our vision of the future is similar to the one you present, it seems nigh impossible to implement. What would be your advice for us?

I guess slow and process are the key words in changes like these.

@nabeel_p, that's a super-nice posts! Thank you so much for your kind words.

It's kind of paradoxical. There's lots of introverts in Edgeryders, lots of people who are not necessarily superconfident in their social interaction. And yet, the collective is cohesive enough to produce, at least for some of us, a sense of warmth and belonging. The best, for me, is when you have some local community _as well as_ the global, Internet-mediated community. Brussels is good that way; maybe a dozen people who are reasonably active on Edgeryders are here, and I can see them often. Also, I like to spend time on the platform, talking to people who I cannot see that often, like I'm doing now with you. And then, of course, I try not to miss the physical gatherings like the OpenVillage Festival. In other words, I try to be part of networks both at the local and at the global scale.

I am sure there are others like you in your local surroundings, in South Africa! For a while there was a group of people that were thinking about setting up an Edgeryders South Africa group: https://edgeryders.eu/c/workspaces/south-africa

As I said, expect some bumps :slight_smile:

